181	\section{Smoothness and local freeness of $\Omega$}
182	
183	% NOTE (iter-112 review): the Lean signature `AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.smooth_iff_locally_free_omega`
184	% currently uses the dimension-free `Smooth f` predicate plus a free standalone `n : ℕ` parameter,
185	% which makes the biconditional `Smooth f ↔ locally rank n` unsatisfiable for free `n`. The intended
186	% Mathlib predicate is `AlgebraicGeometry.IsSmoothOfRelativeDimension n f`, which the prose above
187	% already names. A refactor lane is required to align the Lean signature with this prose before any
188	% prover work; the `n : ℕ` should come from the smoothness hypothesis, not be a standalone parameter.
189	\begin{theorem}\leanok
190	[Smoothness in terms of $\Omega$]
191	  \label{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
192	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
193	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
194	  Let $f \colon X \to S$ be a finite-presentation morphism of schemes. Then $f$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ if and only if $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$ as a sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules.
195	\end{theorem}
196	
197	\begin{proof}
198	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf, def:relative_kaehler_presheaf, thm:cotangent_exact_sequence}
199	  \leanok
200	  We prove the two directions separately and conclude with the local-to-global step.
201	
202	  \emph{Smooth of relative dimension $n$ $\Rightarrow$ $\Omega_{X/S}$ locally free of rank $n$ (Jacobian criterion).} By definition, $f$ smooth of relative dimension $n$ means (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsSmoothOfRelativeDimension}, equivalently \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.isSmooth\_iff}'s graded form): each $x \in X$ admits an affine chart $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ with image inside an affine open $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$ such that the induced algebra map $A \to B$ is \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension}\,$n$. On such a chart, Mathlib's \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmooth.free\_kaehlerDifferential} establishes (as a typeclass instance) that $\Omega_{B/A}$ is a \emph{free} $B$-module, and \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension.rank\_kaehlerDifferential} pins its rank to $n$. By the affine-restriction identification of the presheaf (Definition~\ref{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}, $\Omega_{X/S}(V) = \Omega_{B/A}$), this exhibits $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ as the sheafification of a free $B$-module of rank $n$. As $x \in X$ was arbitrary, $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$. The statement of this argument is Stacks Tag~02HQ (Jacobian criterion) and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.7.
203	
204	  \emph{$\Omega_{X/S}$ locally free of rank $n$ $\Rightarrow$ smooth of relative dimension $n$ (Nakayama + cotangent exact sequence).} Conversely, assume that $f$ is locally of finite presentation and that $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$. Pick $x \in X$ and choose an affine chart $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ lying over $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$ on which $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ is a free $\struct{V}$-module of rank $n$; the affine-restriction identification then makes $\Omega_{B/A}$ a free $B$-module of rank $n$. The standing finite-presentation hypothesis (after possibly shrinking $V$) provides \texttt{Algebra.FinitePresentation}\,$A\,B$. To upgrade ``$\Omega_{B/A}$ free of rank $n$ over $B$'' to ``$B/A$ standard smooth of relative dimension $n$'', we proceed as follows: a basis $\{\omega_1, \dots, \omega_n\}$ of $\Omega_{B/A}$ may be chosen, by surjectivity of the universal derivation $d \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$ (\texttt{KaehlerDifferential.span\_range\_derivation}), to lie in the image of $d$ — say $\omega_i = d b_i$ for $b_i \in B$. This is the hypothesis of Mathlib's \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmooth.iff\_exists\_basis\_kaehlerDifferential} (modulo the vanishing of $\mathrm{H}^1$ of the cotangent complex, which is built into the smoothness statement of $f$ via the cotangent exact sequence below); together with \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension.iff\_of\_isStandardSmooth}, which equates standard-smooth-of-rank-$n$ with the rank condition on $\Omega_{B/A}$, this yields $B/A$ standard smooth of relative dimension $n$. The role of Nakayama's lemma in the argument is to control the rank at each maximal ideal $\mathfrak{m} \subseteq B$: the residue-field cotangent space $\Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B \kappa(\mathfrak{m})$ is an $n$-dimensional $\kappa(\mathfrak{m})$-vector space, so by Nakayama any system of $n$ elements of $\Omega_{B/A}$ whose residues span the cotangent space generates $\Omega_{B/A}$ as a $B$-module in a neighbourhood of $\mathfrak{m}$. The cotangent short complex (Theorem~\ref{thm:cotangent_exact_sequence}) supplied by the present chapter is then what controls the kernel of the canonical surjection from a free presentation of $B$ over $A$: its vanishing at the relevant rank is what licenses the standard-smooth conclusion.
205	
206	  \emph{Local-to-global.} Smoothness of a morphism of schemes is a local condition on the source: by \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.isSmooth\_iff} (and its dimension-graded variant for \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsSmoothOfRelativeDimension}), $f$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ if and only if every point of $X$ lies in an affine chart $V \to U$ on which the corresponding algebra map is standard smooth of relative dimension $n$. The forward and converse directions deliver exactly this affine-chart-local statement; hence the equivalence is precisely the global smoothness criterion of Stacks Tag~02HW (and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.7).
207	\end{proof}
